@Node OpenPicture "PicCon/Project/Open picture"

Choose the picturefile to load. PicCon will load a picture in any picture-
format which you have support for in your datatypes library. The IFF ILBM
datatype specification is delivered as standard with the distribution of
WorkBench3.0, but there's many more in the Public Domain and as shareware
(including JPEG, GIF, PCX and BMP).

After the file has been loaded and depacked (this might take some time,
especially with JPEG-pictures), you'll be presented with a requester
displaying some information on the picture. Click "Ok", and the picture will
now be displayed on your screen. From here on you can start cutting out and
saving pieces of the picture in many different image formats, save this
picture's palette, etc.
@EndNode

@Node OpenIFF "PicCon/Project/Open IFF"

This option exists in addition to @{" Open picture " Link OpenPicture} for one reason only;
if you for any reason don't want to use the datatypes.library, then use this
option to load your pictures.
@EndNode

@Node LoadImage "PicCon/Project/Load image"

This function will load any RAW data and display it as if it were loaded as
an ordinary picture. Useful for loading old RAW files (for which you've
deleted the IFF-file), amongst other things.

When selecting this function, you have to specify the format of the file
you want to load:

Width:       pixelwidth of RAW frame (for sprites: must be 16, 32 or 64)
Heigth:      pixelheight of RAW frame (for sprites: the height of a single
             sprite)
Depth:       number of planes in frame (for sprites: must be 2 (unattached
             sprites) or 4 (attached sprites))
Normal
/HAM
/EHB:        display format

CTRLwords:   valid option for sprites only (is CTRLwords included in the
             RAW spriteframes?)

Packed:      for loading a packed chunky frame

Bitplanes:   load frame as ordinary bitplanes
Interleaved: load frame as interleaved bitplanes
Chunky:      load a chunkypixels frame
Sprites:     load a spriteimages file
WBIcon:      load a workbench icon (this option will ghost the dimensional
             settings, as these will be derived from the .info file)

After setting these options, you're requested to select the screenmode you
want the file to be displayed in. When the frame has been loaded, you're free
to treat it as any file loaded with @{" Open picture " Link OpenPicture} (cut frames, save images
etc).

See also @{" Save image " Link SaveRAW}.
@EndNode

@Node LoadPalette "PicCon/Project/Load palette"

This function loads and inserts any IFF or RAW palette into the picture
currently displayed.

Options:

IFF:        load an IFF palette (as e.g. saved from DPaint
            "Color->Palette->Save") or extract an IFF palette from an IFF
            picture.

RAW 4/8/32: load a RAW palette (as e.g. saved from PicCon).

See also @{" Save palette " Link SavePalette}.
@EndNode

@Node SaveRAW "PicCon/Project/Save image"

Save the picture information contained in the frame in your chosen image
format. If no frame is cut out, this option will save the whole picture
in your specified format. See also: @{" Imageformat " Link RAWformat} and @{" Save data as " Link SaveData}.
The dimensions of the selected frame is normally displayed in the menubar.
@EndNode

@Node SavePalette "PicCon/Project/Save palette"

Save this picture's palette in your specified format. See also:
@{" Palettesave " Link Palettesave} and @{" Save data as " Link SaveData}.
@EndNode

@Node SaveGrid "PicCon/Project/Save grid"

Save a bunch of frames ordered in a grid. Very useful for saving maptiles,
groups of spriteanimationframes etc. This function will save the tiles
you've decided to save (with the @{" Grid settings " Link GridSet}) exactly in the
same way as if you've saved all tiles by hand, and then joined together
the files.

See also: @{" Grid settings " Link GridSet} and @{" Save data as " Link SaveData}.
@EndNode

@Node SaveData "PicCon/Project/Save data as..."

Choose if the saved data should be output as RAW binary, assemblysource,
C source, Pascal source or as a linkable objectmodule.


Data output as assembly sourcecode will look like this:

	SECTION mydata,DATA

	dc.b	$45,$fe,$12,$56,$12,$56,$12,$56,$45,$fe,$12,$45,$fe,$12,$33
	dc.b	$14,$2e,$32,$52,$1f,$fe,$ee,$16,$23,$23,$23,$4f,$ff,$d2,$cd
	.
	.
	.
	dc.b	$a2,$ba,$11,$01



C sourcecode will be saved in this format:

UBYTE myData[] =
{
	0x45,0xfe,0x12,0x56,0x12,0x56,0x12,0x56,0x45,0xfe,0x12,0x45,0xfe,0x12,
	0x33,0x14,0x2e,0x32,0x52,0x1f,0xfe,0xee,0x16,0x23,0x23,0x23,0x4f,0xff,
	.
	.
	.
	0xa2,0xba,0x11,0x01
};


...while Pascal sourcecode will be saved in this format:

Const
	myData : Array[$0..$[# of entries - 1]] of Byte =
(
	$45,$fe,$12,$56,$12,$56,$12,$56,$45,$fe,$12,$45,$fe,$12,
	$33,$14,$2e,$32,$52,$1f,$fe,$ee,$16,$23,$23,$23,$4f,$ff,
	.
	.
	.
	$a2,$ba,$11,$01
);


These examples show how a sourcecode will be saved in byte-format, but
PicCon recognizes if word- or longwordformat would be more appropriate.
E.g.: 16 pixels wide sprites will be saved with two words on each line,
while 64 pixels wide sprites will be saved with 4 longwords on each line.

NOTE: Often you want the saved data to reside in CHIP RAM. To obtain this,
you'll have to specify for your compiler to place it in a chipdata-
section. In assembly you'll do this by appending either ',CHIP' or '_C' to
the 'DATA' keyword, e.g.:

    SECTION mydata,DATA_C

All assemblycompilers may not be completely compatibel with this use of
the CHIPMEM option, check your manual.

In SAS/C, you'll insert the keyword 'chip' between the 'UBYTE' keyword and
the name of your datasection (e.g. myData):

UBYTE chip myData[] =
{
	.
	.
	.
};



When saving as a linkmodule, you'll be asked to specify the external
definition (which is the name of the pointer that points to the beginning
of the datas. This pointer can later be referenced in your sourcecode with
"xref [name]" (assembler) or e.g. "extern void *[name]" (C-source)). You must
also specify type of memory you want the module to be loaded to.
@EndNode

@Node ChangeMode "PicCon/Project/Change screenmode"

Sometimes when you load a picture it will be loaded in a screenmode which
is not very convenient for cutting out pieces of the picture (pixelperfect
framing in SuperHires is not very easy...). Then use this menuchoice to
change the screenmode. All screenmodes contained in your Monitor-drawer
(in DEVS:) will be listed out for you to choose from.
@EndNode

@Node ModifyPal "PicCon/Project/Modify palette"

A standard paletterequester has now been included in PicCon for editing
the paletteentries on the fly. If you've ever used a paletterequester
before, no explanations should be needed on this option. ;)
@EndNode

@Node LoadPrefs "PicCon/Project/Load prefs"

Load and set the preferences in the S:PicCon.prefs file. This is also
automatically done upon starting PicCon. See @{" Save prefs " Link SavePrefs} too.
@EndNode

@Node SavePrefs "PicCon/Project/Save prefs"

Save settings to S:PicCon.prefs. This file will be automatically loaded
upon startup, but can also be done manually by choosing @{" Load prefs " Link LoadPrefs}
from the menu.

Settings included in the preferences file are: savetype (binary/
assemblysource/C source/linkmodule), image format, palettesave format,
last used directory and filenames on loading/saving, plus lots of other
settings and some internal datas.

This option is handy if you grow tired if reselecting the same directory/
filename/menuoptions every time you load PicCon.
@EndNode

@Node InfoBox "PicCon/Project/Info"

Displays information about the picture and the framed box.
@EndNode

@Node About "PicCon/Project/About"

Displays information about the program, the author and the registration.
@EndNode

@Node Iconify "PicCon/Project/Iconify"

Frees up the memory taken by the screen and the window that PicCon uses.
Select the iconify-bar that pops up on the Workbench and click the right
mouse button to reenter the program.
@EndNode

@Node Quit "PicCon/Project/Quit"

Exits program.
@EndNode



@Node Edit "PicCon/Edit"


Menuchoices on the "Edit"-menu:

@{" Cut frame  " Link CutFrame}
@{" Grab frame " Link GrabFrame}
@{" Box frame  " Link BoxFrame}
@{" Set frame  " Link SetFrame}

@{" Free frame " Link FreeFrame}
@{" Autocrop   " Link AutoCrop}
@{" Autoscan   " Link AutoScan}

@{" Flip X     " Link Flip}
@{" Flip Y     " Link Flip}
@EndNode

@Node CutFrame "PicCon/Edit/Cut frame"

After selection of this menuitem, your mousepointer will be followed
by a cross. Upon pressing the left mousebutton, you now have the
possibility of selecting an appropriate piece of your picture for
saving in RAW format. Just keep the left mousebutton pressed while
you drag the mousepointer so that you boxes in the piece you want to
save. See also @{" Grab frame " Link GrabFrame}, @{" Box frame " Link BoxFrame} and @{" Set frame " Link SetFrame}.

Notice that your mousepointer will contain coordinates which tell you the
current position in your picture, and when framing, the current size of
your framebox. Upon 8-pixels boundaries, the coordinates in the
mousepointer will change color to indicate this. Notice also that you don't
need to put your frames on 8-pixel offsets and bytemultiple boundaries to
get a correct saved image. PicCon will automatically adjust, left-align and
blank any trailing bits and bytes on the boxed frames upon any
saveoperations.

If your picture is 'open' (clearly seperated items on the screen) you
can use the @{" Autocrop " Link AutoCrop} option after selection to avoid having to
do pixelperfect boxing of your frame.

If you misplace the selection, you might want to use the @{" Set frame " Link SetFrame} option
to correct some of the coordinates.
@EndNode

@Node GrabFrame "PicCon/Edit/Grab frame"

If you keep the graphical objects you want to cut out in boxes (f.ex. to
guide your graphician, so he doesn't draw too big objects), then you can
use this option to frame the images. Just select the pen by which the box
is drawn, and click somewhere inside the box.

Notice that the box have to be complete, "holes" in the boxwalls will make
the box unusable.

If you've got many frames stored in this "boxed" format, you might consider
using the @{" Autoscan " Link AutoScan} function, which will save all your boxes in one go.

The second time you use this option, you will not be requested for the
boxpen, as it's assumed that it is the same as the first time you use this
function. Change the selected boxpen with the @{" Grabpen " Link GrabPen} setting.

See also @{" Cut frame " Link CutFrame}, @{" Box frame " Link BoxFrame} and @{" Set frame " Link SetFrame} plus the quick
tutorial: @{" Grab frame " Link GrabFrameTut}.
@EndNode

@Node BoxFrame "PicCon/Edit/Box frame"

This function let you cut out your frame with a fixed sized box. The size
of the box is set from the current frame, or manually in case there is no
cutted frame.

This is handy if you want to cut several pieces with the same size
out of your picture. See also @{" Cut frame " Link SetFrame}, @{" Grab frame " Link GrabFrame} and @{" Set frame " Link SetFrame}.
@EndNode

@Node SetFrame "PicCon/Edit/Set frame"

Instead of selecting a frame by dragging out the framebox, you can use
this function to manually input the coordinates of the corners of the
framebox. See also @{" Cut frame " Link CutFrame}, @{" Grab frame " Link GrabFrame} and @{" Box frame " Link BoxFrame}.

This function is also handy if you miss slightly when you use the mouse
to select the framebox; just pop up the coordinates inputbox and modify
the coordinates.
@EndNode

@Node FreeFrame "PicCon/Edit/Free frame"

Frees the selected framebounds (by setting the max dimensions).
@EndNode

@Node AutoCrop "PicCon/Edit/Autocrop"

After framing a piece of the picture, you might want to use this option
to make the framing 'perfect' (no extra space included). This function
excludes the need to do pixelperfect framing.
@EndNode

@Node AutoScan "PicCon/Edit/Autoscan"

If you're working on large projects, it's very timeconsuming to manually
cut and save the individual frames. With a bit of planning and the help
of this option, you can greatly reduce the time spent in PicCon. First
you have to keep all the graphical objects in boxes, as you would with the
@{" Grab frame " Link GrabFrame} function (and all boxes have to be in the same color).
Second, select your wanted imageformat (e.g. Bitplanes, Sprites or
whatever). Now use this option to get PicCon to automatically scan and
save all boxed frames in one go. The frames will be saved to a single file,
while the offsets to the different frames in the file will be saved to
another file with the same name, but with ".offset" appended to the
filename.

The frames will be saved top-to-bottom and left-to-right, which means that
frames with lower topmost y coordinates will be appended first to your
savefile, while frames with identic topmost y coordinates will be saved
according to leftmost x coordinates (lowest leftmost x coordinate -> saved
first).

Note that it is the inner box that will be saved (the borders are not 
included). So to save e.g. a 64x64 frame, you'd have to make a 66x66
pixels wide box (including the borders).

Note also that this function will work exactly as if you'd cutted and
saved all the frames individually, and then joined the files afterwards.

The .offset-file will consist of ASCII-text, in this format:

frame_000	EQU		$00000000
frame_001	EQU		$00004000
frame_002	EQU		$00007800
.
.
frame_xxx	EQU		$yyyyyyyy

(Labels on the left side, offsets on the right side. This format should be
compatible with most assemblers).

See also the quick tutorial: @{" Autoscan " Link AutoScanTut}.
@Endnode

@Node Flip "PicCon/Edit/Flip"

Will flip your selected frame in the chosen direction (if no frame is cutted,
the whole picture will be flipped).

This option will be useful if you don't want to have flip-routines in your
code, but rather include the flipped frames as binary data.
@EndNode

@Node Settings "PicCon/Settings"

@{" Imagesave     " Link RAWformat}
@{" Palettesave   " Link Palettesave}
@{" Grid settings " Link GridSet}

@{" Grabpen       " Link GrabPen}
@EndNode

@Node RAWformat "PicCon/Settings/Imageformat"

The settings in this window is for selecting the way the boxed frame
will be saved when choosing @{" Save image " Link SaveRAW} in the @{" Project " Link Project} menu.

Settings in the "Imageformat"-window:

@{" Bitplanes   " Link BPlanes}
@{" Interleaved " Link Interl}
@{" Mask        " Link BlitMask}
@{" Chunky      " Link Chunky}
@{" Sprites     " Link Sprite}
@{" WB icon     " Link WBIcon}
@{" IFF ILBM    " Link RAWIFF}
@EndNode

@Node BPlanes "PicCon/Settings/Imagesave/Bitplanes"

Set RAW save to ordinary bitplaneformat:



          <- framewidth ->

          +--------------+
          |              |     ^
          |              |     |
          |  Bitplane 0  | frameheight
          |              |     |
          |              |     |
          +--------------+     v
          |              |     ^
          |              |     |
          |  Bitplane 1  | frameheight
          |              |     |
          |              |     |
          +--------------+     v
          |              |     ^
          |              |     |
          |  Bitplane 2  | frameheight
          |              |     |
          |              |     |
          +--------------+     v
                 |
                 |
                 .
                 .
                etc


In conjunction with this format, you must also specify the "Blitterwords"
option. If you set this format to any other than "None", an extra row of
words (16 pixels, 2 bytes) will be saved to either the left or the right
(or both) of the raw bitplaneframe. This is necessary to be able to use
the blitterchip's shiftmodus.

(Check your copy of the Amiga Hardware Reference Manual.)
@EndNode

@Node Interl "PicCon/Settings/Imagesave/Interleaved"

Set RAW save to interleaved format (useful for blittergraphics and
fast displays):

  +--------------+--------------+--------------+
  |              |              |              |
  |              |              |              |
  |              |              |              |
  |              |              |              |
  |  Bitplane 0  |  Bitplane 1  |  Bitplane 2  |-- . . etc
  |              |              |              |
  |              |              |              |
  |              |              |              |
  |              |              |              |
  +--------------+--------------+--------------+


In conjunction with this format, you must also specify the "Blitterwords"
option. If you set this format to any other than "None", an extra row of
words (16 pixels, 2 bytes) will be saved to either the left or the right
(or both) of each of the interleaved raw planeframes. This is necessary to
be able to use the blitterchip's shiftmodus.

(Check your copy of the Amiga Hardware Reference Manual.)
@EndNode

@Node BlitMask "PicCon/Settings/Imagesave/Mask"

If this option is selected upon saving, a mask of the current frame
will be created and saved. The mask is created by OR'ing all the
bitplaneframes together, effectively making a 'shadow' of the object
within the frame. Such frames are necessary to use when you want to
animate or move blitter objects on top of some backgroundgraphics.
Otherwise some of the background bitplanes will "crash" with your
object's bitplanes. Just set up the blitter (or use the CPU) to perform
this logic function on all common background- and objectplanes:

       bckgnd   mask    result

         0       0        0
         0       1        0
         1       0        1
         1       1        0


(result = ~mask & bckgnd)

This is referred to as the cookie-cut method in the Amiga Hardware
Reference Manual.

Along with this option, you must also choose if you want to save the
frame with blitterwords (see @{" Bitplanes " Link BPlanes} or @{" Interleaved " Link Interl}), and if
you want to save one maskframe, or if you want to save multiple interleaved
frames:

If the "Single plane" option is set, the selected frame will be saved as a
blittermask in this format:


             framewidth
          +--------------+
    ^     |              |
    |     |              |
    |     |              |
    |     |              |
          |              |
  frame-  |     Mask     |
  height  |              | ...where the bits in "Mask" is made up
          |              | by OR'ing together the individual bit-
    |     |              | planes in the frame.
    |     |              |
    |     |              |
    v     +--------------+




If the "Interleaved" option is set, the selected frame will be saved as a
blittermask in this format:

  +--------------+--------------+          +--------------+
  |              |              |          |              |
  |              |              |          |              |
  |              |              |          |              |
  |              |              |          |              |
  |    Mask      |    Mask      |......... |    Mask      |
  |   plane0     |   plane1     |          |   planeN     |
  |              |              |          |              |
  |              |              |          |              |
  |              |              |          |              |
  +--------------+--------------+          +--------------+


The mask will be saved as many times as there's bitplanes in the
picture (N).

This format makes it possible to mask out unwanted bits in
all bitplanes with only one blitteroperation (if you've made
your screen interleaved).
@EndNode

@Node Chunky "PicCon/Settings/Imagesave/Chunky"

Chunkymode is an often used IBM-PC format, but will also be used
in the Amigascene with the introduction of the Akikochip in the
CD32-console.

In chunkymode, 1 byte is saved for each pixel in the picture.
E.g.:
     If you've got 5 bitplanes, with bits set in planes 0 and 3, and
    unset in planes 1, 2 and 4, the pixel will have this value:

    % 0 0 0 0 1 0 0 1 = $09 = dec 9

 bit# 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0  (bits in unused bitplanes will be unset)


Along with the "Chunky"-option, you must also specify the "Packed"-setting.
If you don't select packed chunky, the frame will be saved in the format
explained above. If you do set the "Packed"-option, the pixels from each
byte will be leftshifted to remove any superfluous bits (e.g. in the above
example we'll get the value: %01001xyz, where xyz will be shifted in from the
next byte in the framedata).
@EndNode

@Node Sprite "PicCon/Settings/Imagesave/Sprite"

Will set RAW saveformat to Amiga sprites.

You must also set the spritewidth, attachment and CTRLwords options:

Spritewidth is set to either 16, 32 or 64 pixels. 32 and 64 pixels wide
sprites might only be used with the AGA chipset. Spriteheight is
unlimited on any version of the Amiga chipsets.

For displaying sprites with more than 3 colors, you'll have to make
them attached. This means that you must overlap two sprites to get
15 colors to choose from. The sprites will be saved like this:


          +--------------+
          |              |
          |              |
          |   Sprite 0   |
          |              |
          |              |
          +--------------+
          |              |
          |              |
          |   Sprite 1   |
          |              |
          |              |
          +--------------+

(Check your copy of the Amiga Hardware Reference Manual.)


Setting the "CTRLwords" option will make the program append some blank
bytes in front of and behind the sprite(s) when saved. The bytes in front
of the sprite is used to set position, attachment and other control bits.
The bytes behind the actual imagedata is used for spritetermination.

The number of bytes appended to the actual spritedata will depend upon
your selected spritewidth. If you're using 16 pixels wide sprites, 2 words
will be appended in front of the sprite(s) and 2 words behind. For 32
pixels wide sprites, you'll get 2 longwords extra in front and behind, and
for 64 pixels wide sprites it'll be 2 double longwords.

(Check your copy of the Amiga Hardware Reference Manual.)


Notice that if your frame is wider than the width of one sprite (16, 32
or 64 pixels), several sprites will be appended to the same savefile. E.g.
a 48-pixels wide frame of 16-pixels wide, attached sprites with CTRLwords
will be saved like this:

          +--------------+
          |   CTRLwords  |
          +--------------+      ^
          |              |      |
          |  sprite #0   |
          |              | spriteheight
          | planes 0 + 1 |
          |              |      |
          +--------------+      v
          | termination  |
          +--------------+
          +--------------+
          |   CTRLwords  |
          +--------------+      ^
          |              |      |
          |  sprite #0   |
          |              | spriteheight
          | planes 2 + 3 |
          |              |      |
          +--------------+      v
          | termination  |
          +--------------+
          |   CTRLwords  |
          +--------------+      ^
          |              |      |
          |  sprite #1   |
          |              | spriteheight
          | planes 0 + 1 |
          |              |      |
          +--------------+      v
          | termination  |
          +--------------+
          +--------------+
          |   CTRLwords  |
          +--------------+      ^
          |              |      |
          |  sprite #1   |
          |              | spriteheight
          | planes 2 + 3 |
          |              |      |
          +--------------+      v
          | termination  |
          +--------------+
          |   CTRLwords  |
          +--------------+      ^
          |              |      |
          |  sprite #2   |
          |              | spriteheight
          | planes 0 + 1 |
          |              |      |
          +--------------+      v
          | termination  |
          +--------------+
          +--------------+
          |   CTRLwords  |
          +--------------+      ^
          |              |      |
          |  sprite #2   |
          |              | spriteheight
          | planes 2 + 3 |
          |              |      |
          +--------------+      v
          | termination  |
          +--------------+
@EndNode

@Node WBIcon "PicCon/Settings/Imagesave/WBIcon"

This option sets the image format of the savefile to standard Amiga
workbench icon. The format and type of the icon must also be set:

Formats supported:

WBDISK:    Same type as e.g. the RAM Disk icon.
WBDRAWER:  Same type as any drawer in your workbench.
WBTOOLS:   Executable files (and scriptfiles).
WBPROJECT: Files that need a program to "treat them", e.g. docfiles.
WBGARBAGE: Same type as the standard Amiga garbage can.
WBDEVICE:  I don't know what kind of files that use this icontype, as I don't
           think I have ever seen a "device-icon". I can't save icons of this
           format either, as they have no default in the 3.0 workbench (well,
           not in my workbench, that is). Maybe this is a future format?
WBKICK:    These icons can be saved under my configuration, but I still don't
           know what they are good for, as I have never seen any files with
           a WBKICK icon.
WBAPPICON: Same story here as with WBDEVICE, it don't seem to be possible for
           me to obtain specifications on this iconformat, as the defaulticon
           can't be loaded with the icon.library function "GetDefDiskObject".


Gadgettypes supported:

Complement:  If this option is set, your iconimage will be complemented when
             picked by the user.
Backfill:    If this option is set, your iconimage will be "backfilled" when
             picked by the user.
Image:       Set this option if you want your icon to have two different
             images, one for when the icongadget is up, and one for when it's
             pressed down. If this option is on upon choosing @{" Save image " Link SaveRAW},
             you'll be prompted to cut out another frame for use as the
             "selectrender image" (icongadget down). The frame that you've
             already picked will be used as the icongadget up image.


When you specify the filename of the workbench icon, you don't need to
include the .info extension, as this will be done automatically.

If you choose to @{" Save image " Link SaveRAW} with this option on, the @{" Save data as " Link SaveData}
settings will be ignored, as workbench icons are always pure binaries.
@EndNode

@Node RAWIFF "PicCon/Settings/Imagesave/IFF"

Frames saved with this option on will be saved as IFF brushes/pictures
(useful for inclusion in drawing packages, DTP programs etc).
If you choose to @{" Save image " Link SaveRAW} with this option on, the @{" Save data as " Link SaveData}
settings will be ignored, as IFF frames are always pure binaries.
@EndNode

@Node Palettesave "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave"

The settings in this window is for selecting the way the picturepalette
will be saved when choosing @{" Save palette " Link SavePalette} in the @{" Project " Link Project} menu.

Settings in the "Palettesave"-window:

@{" 4 bits     " Link 4bits}
@{" 8 bits     " Link 8bits}
@{" 32 bits    " Link 32bits}
@{" LoadRGB4   " Link Load4}
@{" LoadRGB32  " Link Load32}
@{" IFF        " Link PalIFF}

@{" Copperlist " Link Copperlist}

@EndNode

@Node 4bits "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave/4bits"

Will save out your palette in the standard old chipset and enhanced
chipset formats (4-bits-per-gun, 1 word per color).

E.g.:
White is $0fff, red is $0f00 and purple is $0f0f.

             ^blue component
            ^green component
           ^red component
          ^unused
@EndNode

@Node 8bits "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave/8bits"

Will save out your palette in the new AGA chipset format (8-bits-per-gun,
2 words (1 longword) per color).

E.g.:
White is $00ffffff, red is $00ff0000 and purple is $00ff00ff.

                ^^blue component
              ^^green component
            ^^red component
          ^^unused
@EndNode

@Node 32bits "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave/32bits"

Will save out your palette in the internal systemformat (32-bits-per-gun,
3 longwords per color)).

E.g.:
White is $ffffffffffffffffffffffff and purple is $ffffffff00000000ffffffff.

                          ^^^^^^^^blue component
                  ^^^^^^^^green component
          ^^^^^^^^red component
@EndNode

@Node Load4 "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave/LoadRGB4"

Will save the palette as an array ready to be passed to the graphics.library
function "LoadRGB4".

Look up the autodocs specification of "LoadRGB4" if this is unclear.
@EndNode

@Node Load32 "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave/LoadRGB32"

Will save the palette as an array ready to be passed to the graphics.library
function "LoadRGB32".

Look up the autodocs specification of "LoadRGB32" if this is unclear.
@EndNode

@Node PalIFF "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave/IFF"

Saves out the palette in IFF format (e.g. for reading in DPaint). If this
option is set, the @{" Save data as " Link SaveData} setting will be ignored
(IFF files are always of binary format).
@EndNode

@Node Copperlist "PicCon/Settings/Palettesave/Copperlist"

Will save out your palette as a list of commands that the Amiga graphics-
coprocessor (a.k.a. COPPER) understands. Insert the palette coppercommands
into your own custom copperlist to make use of the paletteentries.

PicCon knows the format of both OCS/ECS and AGA chipsets, and will save
in the appropriate format according to the number of bits-per-gun specified:

4 bits-per-gun: OCS/ECS copperlist.

8 bits-per-gun: AGA copperlist.

The other options (32bits, LoadRGB4, LoadRGB32 and IFF) will ignore the
Copperlist setting.
@EndNode

@Node GridSet "PicCon/Settings/Grid settings"

Imagine this: you are coding a game where you need loads of background
graphicstiles (say, 16x16 pixels wide, which are then combined to make
bigger objects in the background). To get maximum speed (minimum CPU/blitter
load), you need to have each one of them in interleaved RAW format. What do
you do? You'd probably save out the whole bitmap with an IFF-converter and
then code your own custom formatconverter to get the tiles the way you
wanted them. This is not necessary any more, as PicCon is able to save a
grid of frames in any of the usual formats, except as IFF ILBMs or as
Workbench icons.

The options in the grid settings window are explained below:

Grid orientation (horizontal/vertical): choose to save the tiles in either
   left-to-right (horizontal) or top-to-bottom (vertical) fashion.

(As an example, let's say we've got a 3x3 grid of frames:

          +---+---+---+
          |   |   |   |
          | 1 | 2 | 3 |
          |   |   |   |
          +---+---+---+
          |   |   |   |
          | 4 | 5 | 6 |
          |   |   |   |
          +---+---+---+
          |   |   |   |
          | 7 | 8 | 9 |
          |   |   |   |
          +---+---+---+

With horizontal orientation, these frames will be saved in this order
1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9, while if you set vertical orientation, the internal
positions in the saved file will be like this: 1,4,7,2,5,8,3,6,9.)

Blockwidth: decide the width in number of pixels in the individual tiles.
Blockheight: decide the height in number of pixels in the individual tiles.

Blocks horiz.: number of blocks horizontally. (3 in the above example)
Blocks vert.: number of blocks vertically. (3 in the above example)

Total #: The total number of blocks you want to save (if no blocks are
         "missing" in your chunk of frames, this number will usually be
         (blocks horiz.)*(blocks vert.)). (9 in the above example)


Note that your chunk of frames to be saved must have the upper left pixel
in the absolute upper left corner of the screen (at (0,0)).
The gridsave option will not be influenced by any box you've cutted in the
picture. The individual tiles will all be saved in the format you select
in the @{" Imagesave " Link RAWformat} window. All tiles will be appended
together in a single file.

See also @{" Save grid " Link SaveGrid}.
@EndNode

@Node GrabPen "PicCon/Settings/Grabpen"

Choose a new boxpen to search for in the @{" Grab frame " Link GrabFrame} function.
@EndNode

@Node Misc "PicCon/Misc"

Menuchoices on the "Misc"-menu:

@{" Pen usage in frame  " Link PenUsage}
@{" Remap pens in frame " Link Remap}
@{" Trace unused pens   " Link Trace}
@{" Convert EHB->normal " Link EHBNorm}
@{" Reselect systempens " Link Reselect}
@EndNode

@Node PenUsage "PicCon/Misc/Pen usage in frame"

This function makes a histogram of the relative usage of the pens in the
selected frame.
@EndNode

@Node Remap "PicCon/Misc/Remap pens in frame"

I guess this function was pretty high on the "most wanted feature" list by
the coders? (It's not included in DPaint, and the version of this function
implemented in Brilliance can't work on selected areas of the screen.)

Anyway, it gives you the possibility of either moving or interchanging all
pixels of a pen to another pen. This function works inside your selected
frame.

Do not confuse the "Move" and "Swap" functions in this feature with the
corresponding calls in the "Modify palette" option. Nothing is actually
done with the values of the paletteentries, but with the bitrepresentations
of the individual pixels in the bitmap.

See also the quick tutorial: @{" Remap pens in frame " Link RemapTut}.
@Endnode

@Node Trace "PicCon/Misc/Trace unused pens"

This function will find all the unused and duplicated pens in the palette
and "push" them at the end (by moving all pixels set with other pens into
the front of the palette). If the number of unused and duplicated palette-
entries are so high that 1 or more bitplanes are not needed (say, if you
only use 13 pens in a 5 bitplanes picture (which has 32 pens available), it
would be possible to render the exact same picture in 4 bitplanes), you'll
also be asked if you want to remove the superfluous bitplane(s).

See also the quick tutorial: @{" Trace unused pens " Link TraceTut}.
@EndNode

@Node EHBNorm "PicCon/Misc/Convert EHB->normal"

This function converts a 6 bitplanes picture in extra halfbrite modus (with
32 editable paletteentries) to an ordinary 6 bitplanes picture (with 64
editable paletteentries).

This makes it possible to use all the other simple "imageprocessing" tools
in PicCon to work on these pictures.
@EndNode

@Node Reselect "PicCon/Misc/Reselect systempens"

If for any reason the selected systempens (the pens which are used to
render the menubar, requestergadgets etc) should make something hard to
read, use this function to reselect them.

(The systempens might get changed if you use the paletterequester, and
you should then use this function if they get hard to read (or just ugly
to look at). This also applies if you use the @{" Load palette " Link LoadPalette}
option).
@EndNode

@Node History "PicCon/History"

History:

   .
   .
   .
   |
   |

v1.07:
  - fixed many small bugs and quirks (as usual)
  - now perfect handling of the smallest bitmaps (e.g. DPaint-
   Brushes)

v1.08:
  - included option to save data as linkobject
  - included loading of raw- and IFF-palettes
  - option to save palette as IFF was added
  - new imagesave format; IFF
  - raw savefiles now have frameinformation in the commentfield
  - loading of RAW images and WorkBench icons implemented
  - now possible to save multiple sprites in one go

v2.00:
  - removed bug that sometimes caused crash upon exit
  - paletterequester
  - option to iconify PicCon added
  - fixed a bug that made it difficult to specify memorytype and
   external definition name on palette linkobject files
  - no longer needs datatypes.library to be present
  - IFF ILBM loading without datatypes.library
  - IDCMP_VANILLAKEY - no need to hold right Amigakey when using
   hotkeys any longer (more like DPaint ;-)
  - now saves WBicons at any width (don't have to be multiples of
   16 pixels)
  - fixed icontype bug on icons that use drawerstructures
  - no longer needs iffparse.library to be present
  - added option to save frames with extra blitterwords attached
   either left or right (or both) for easy blittershift operations
  - added option to save chunky images in packed format
  - added option to load raw chunky images in packed format
  - quick automatic framegrabs with less userinteraction is now
   possible ("Grab frame")
  - image and palette saveformats displayed in titlebar at all times,
   along with the coordinates of the framebox
  - new saveoption: Grids (nice for saving e.g. 100s of blocks of
   graphical datas for maptiles/spriteframes/...)
  - functions to compress pens and remove superfluous bitplanes added
  - conversion: EHB --> 64 colors normal
  - added control of systempens (all menus/requesters/gadgets should
   be fully visible on all but the most extreme palettes (like all
   paletteentries having e.g. the same value))
  - new autoscan feature
  - added option to save data as Pascal sourcecode
  - made more functional demoversion
@EndNode

